AB  - Chapter 26 Urgent Communication During Public Health Crises Reaching Linguistically Diverse Populations Victoria Ledford, Victoria LedfordSearch for more papers by this authorA. Susana Ramírez, A. Susana RamírezSearch for more papers by this authorXiaoli Nan, Xiaoli NanSearch for more papers by this author Victoria Ledford, Victoria LedfordSearch for more papers by this authorA. Susana Ramírez, A. Susana RamírezSearch for more papers by this authorXiaoli Nan, Xiaoli NanSearch for more papers by this author Book Editor(s):Pilar Ortega, Pilar Ortega Accreditation Council for Graduate Medical Education, IL, USASearch for more papers by this authorGlenn Martínez, Glenn Martínez University of Texas at San Antonio, TX, USASearch for more papers by this authorMaichou Lor, Maichou Lor University of Wisconsin-Madison, WI, USASearch for more papers by this authorA. Susana Ramírez, A. Susana Ramírez University of California-Merced, CA, USASearch for more papers by this author First published: 21 March 2024 https://doi.org/10.1002/9781119853855.ch26 AboutPDFPDF ToolsRequest permissionExport citationAdd to favoritesTrack citation ShareShareShare a linkShare onEmailFacebookTwitterLinkedInRedditWechat Summary Public health crises – whether localized, such as wildfires, or global, such as infectious disease pandemics – are a unique context for health communication. During public health crises, clear, accurate, and actionable information must be disseminated to multiple audiences swiftly, even as the science and context may be evolving quickly. The challenges for effectively reaching linguistically diverse audiences are multiplied by public health crises. In this chapter, we provide context and theory for understanding potential pitfalls in communicating during public health emergencies and review relevant theoretical frameworks and the research evidence to guide effective communication efforts to mitigate disparities in access to health information and resultant inequities in health outcomes. REFERENCES Ministry of the Interior and Safety . Disaster Alerts 2021 . https://www.safekorea.go.kr/idsiSFK/neo/sfk/cs/sfc/dis/disasterMsgList.jsp?menuSeq=679 Google Scholar Lim , J.R. , Jun , H. , and Ledford , V. ( 2022 ). LGBTQ+ Individuals' intersectional stigma experiences during COVID-19 outbreaks: effective risk communication to motivate testing, tracing, and treatment . PxyArXiv https://doi.org/10.31234/osf.io/2nbmj . 10.31234/osf.io/2nbmj Google Scholar Cha , S. and Smith , J. ( 2020 ). South Korea Tracks New Coronavirus Outbreak in Seoul nightclubs . Reuters . https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-health-coronavirus-southkorea-idUKKBN22K0SX (accessed 7 April 2022). Google Scholar COVID-19 Map. Johns Hopkins Coronavirus Resource Center . https://coronavirus.jhu.edu/map.html (accessed 19 April 2022) Google Scholar Sauer , M.A. , Truelove , S. , Gerste , A.K. , and Limaye , R.J. ( 2021 ). A failure to communicate? How public messaging has strained the COVID-19 response in the United States . Health Secur. 19 ( 1 ): 65 – 74 . 10.1089/hs.2020.0190 CASPubMedWeb of Science®Google Scholar Nelson , C. , Lurie , N. , Wasserman , J. , and Zakowski , S. ( 2007 ). Conceptualizing and defining public health emergency preparedness . Am. J. Public Health 97 ( Suppl 1 ): S9 – S11 . 10.2105/AJPH.2007.114496 PubMedGoogle Scholar London , A.J. ( 2016 ). Research in a Public Health Crisis: The Integrative Approach to Managing the Moral Tensions . Oxford University Press . https://academic.oup.com/book/24612/chapter/187920549 (accessed 7 August 2022). 10.1093/med/9780190270742.003.0007 Google Scholar CDC ( 2022 ). CDC Museum COVID-19 Timeline . Centers for Disease Control and Prevention . https://www.cdc.gov/museum/timeline/covid19.html (accessed 7 August 2022). Google Scholar CDC ( 2020 ). Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) . Centers for Disease Control and Prevention . https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/science/about-epidemiology/identifying-source-outb