AB  - Chapter 8 Decoding Global Indoor Health Perception on Social Media Through NLP and Transformer Deep Learning Mehdi Ashayeri, Mehdi Ashayeri School of Architecture, College of Arts and Media, Southern Illinois University Carbondale, Carbondale, IL, USASearch for more papers by this author Mehdi Ashayeri, Mehdi Ashayeri School of Architecture, College of Arts and Media, Southern Illinois University Carbondale, Carbondale, IL, USASearch for more papers by this author Book Editor(s):Narjes Abbasabadi, Narjes Abbasabadi University of Washington, Seattle, USASearch for more papers by this authorMehdi Ashayeri, Mehdi Ashayeri Southern Illinois University Carbondale, Carbondale, USASearch for more papers by this author First published: 19 April 2024 https://doi.org/10.1002/9781394172092.ch8 AboutPDFPDF ToolsRequest permissionExport citationAdd to favoritesTrack citation ShareShareShare a linkShare onEmailFacebookTwitterLinkedInRedditWechat Summary The primary objectives of this chapter are to (a) scrutinize the theoretical foundation of digital media and communication technologies in understanding modern cities, along with the associated challenges and opportunities; (b) conduct a comprehensive review of the application of social media data in environmental health research, focusing on indoor and outdoor air exposures, while also reviewing current methodologies and identifying existing gaps in the field; and (c) undertake research utilizing the latest frameworks in natural language processing ( NLP ), employing transformer deep learning techniques, to evaluate occupants' feedback. This human feedback, obtained from geo-tagged big textual data on the X (formerly known as Twitter) platform, is used to explore the effects of stay-at-home orders on indoor air quality ( IAQ ) perceptions globally. This analysis covers the first year of the pandemic and juxtaposes these insights with the baseline data from 2019. In this pilot study, we utilized transformer models, specifically the robustly optimized BERT pretraining approach ( RoBERTa ) algorithm, a pre-trained model based on the X data, for sentiment analysis. Results indicate an increase in negative perceptions of IAQ among occupants in 2020 compared to the 2019 baseline. The research emphasizes the untapped potential of social media analytics in shaping and refining environmental health strategies, particularly in the context of indoor environments. Findings underscore a pressing need for architects, planners, and policy-makers to prioritize IAQ in design considerations, especially in light of changing global dynamics like pandemics. References Abdulaali , H.S. , Usman , I.M.S. , and Hanafiah , M.M. ( 2020 ). Online Review Analysis of Perceived Indoor Environmental Quality (IEQ) at Former Green Certified Hotels in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia . Journal of Xi'an University Of Architecture & Technology 14 : 659 – 670 . Google Scholar Allen , J.G. and Ibrahim , A.M. ( 2021 ). Indoor Air Changes and Potential Implications for SARS-CoV-2 Transmission . The Journal of American Medical Association 325 ( 20 ): 2112 . https://doi.org/10.1001/jama.2021.5053 . 10.1001/jama.2021.5053 CASPubMedWeb of Science®Google Scholar Antons , D. , Grünwald , E. , Cichy , P. , and Salge , T.O. ( 2020 ). The Application of Text Mining Methods in Innovation Research: Current State, Evolution Patterns, and Development Priorities . R&D Management 50 ( 3 ): 329 – 351 . https://doi.org/10.1111/radm.12408 . 10.1111/radm.12408 Web of Science®Google Scholar Barbieri , F. , Camacho-Collados , J. , Neves , L. , and Espinosa-Anke , L. ( 2020 ). TweetEval: Unified Benchmark and Comparative Evaluation for Tweet Classification . arXiv http://arxiv.org/abs/2010.12421 . Google Scholar Bardhan , I.R. , Demirkan , H. , Kannan , P.K. et al. ( 2010 ). An Interdisciplinary Perspective on IT Services Management and Service Science . Journal of Management Information Systems 26 ( 4 ): 13 – 64 . https://doi.org/10.2753/MIS0742-122226040