AU  - Giudice, Catharina
AU  - Rublee, Caitlin S.
T2  - Annals of emergency medicine
AB  - In November 2022, the United Nations Climate Change Conference (COP27) took place in Egypt, bringing together global leaders to discuss the issue of climate change. The conference marked a shift in the focus of climate negotiations, with greater emphasis placed on adaptation and resilience strategies rather than on mitigation. The outcome of COP27 was the creation of a loss-and-damage fund to support countries most affected by the climate crisis. The message from the conference was clear, which was as follows: it is no longer possible to focus only on preventing serious consequences of climate change, and it is therefore necessary to invest in adaptation efforts, with special attention to the needs of the most vulnerable people. Anthropogenic climate change is altering the pattern, severity, and frequency of diseases that we see as frontline clinicians. It is increasingly contributing to heat-related illnesses, water- and vector-borne diseases, respiratory and cardiovascular diseases, accidental and nonaccidental trauma, and mental health disorders.1Sorensen C.J. Salas R.N. Rublee C. et al.Clinical implications of climate change on US emergency medicine: challenges and opportunities.Ann Emerg Med. 2020; 76: 168-178Abstract Full Text Full Text PDF PubMed Scopus (23) Google Scholar Heat waves, floodings, and wildfires are intensifying, resulting in disruption in health care delivery and surges in acute care demand.2Salas R.N. Solomon C.G. The climate crisis—health and care delivery.N Engl J Med. 2019; 381: e13Crossref PubMed Scopus (39) Google Scholar The effects are disproportionately affecting vulnerable populations such as specific racial and ethnic groups, those living in poverty, those at extremes of age, and those with chronic medical conditions. In the United States alone, the health costs related to climate change and air pollution are already estimated to far exceed $800 billion per year and are expected to increase further.3De Alwis D. Limaye V.S. The Costs of Climate Inaction: The Economic Burden of Fossil Fuels and Climate Change on Health in the United States. MSCCH, NRDC and WHPCA, 2021Google Scholar For years, physicians across specialties have recognized the link between climate and human health and have engaged in related research, advocacy, policy, and education. The Medical Society Consortium on Climate and Health, which was founded in 2016, now has membership participation of 46 national medical societies—including the American College of Emergency Physicians (ACEP)—representing over 70% of US physicians.4Medical Society Consortium on Climate and Health Summary 2022.https://medsocietiesforclimatehealth.org/aboutGoogle Scholar It is becoming standard for physicians, and emergency physicians specifically, to recognize climate change as an important global health issue. However, many experience significant constraints in engaging in climate action at a personal and professional level.5Kotcher J. Maibach E. Miller J. et al.Views of health professionals on climate change and health: a multinational survey study.Lancet Planet Health. 2021; 5: e316-e323Abstract Full Text Full Text PDF PubMed Scopus (130) Google Scholar As we enter an era in which climate change adaptation and resilience are becoming exceedingly important, what can emergency physicians do within the purview of their clinical practice to improve climate health outcomes in their communities? Taking advantage of targeted quality patient education in the emergency department (ED) is a low-cost and high-yield way for emergency physicians to improve climate-related health outcomes. In 2018, ACEP released a policy statement emphasizing the important role of emergency medicine in addressing climate crisis. Among 6 action items, ACEP highlighted our role in “educat(ing) patients on appropriate precautions in extreme weather, avoidance of exacerbation triggers, early identification of exacerbations, and temporizing measures when needed.”6American College of Emergency PhysiciansImpact of climate change on public health and implications for emergency medicine.Ann Emerg Med. 2018; 72: e49Abstract Full Text Full Text PDF PubMed Scopus (2) Google Scholar Oftentimes, encounters in the ED are the only contact that at-risk populations have with the health care system. Therefore, these brief encounters are invaluable opportunities to provide high-quality education relevant to the acute patient presentation and prevent mild climate-related illnesses from turning into life-threatening disease exacerbations, infections, or injuries. Within this framework, emergency physicians ought to adhere to the following aspects: (1) understand how the communities they serve are being affected by climate change, (2) identify climate-related ED presentations and patients most at risk from severe health effects of climate change,7Balbus J.M. Malina C. Identifying vulnerable subpopulations for climate change health effects in the United States.J Occup Environ Med. 2009; 51: 33-37Crossref PubMed Scopus (235) Google Scholar,8Crimmins A. Balbus J. Gamble J.L. Beard C.B. et al.The Impacts of Climate Change on Human Health in the United States: A Scientific Assessment. U.S. Global Change Research Program.http://dx.doi.org/10.7930/J0R49NQXDate: 2016Date accessed: July 7, 2023Google Scholar and (3) deliver high-yield verbal or written education focused on how to improve personal resilience and minimize risk. Emergency medicine has long capitalized on opportunities to deliver preventive services to reduce the burden of disease and injury in populations at risk. For instance, patient-physician conversations are a common practice for public health conditions, such as tobacco cessation,9Pelletier J.H. Strout T.D. Baumann M.R. A systematic review of smoking cessation interventions in the emergency setting.Am J Emerg Med. 2014; 32: 713-724Abstract Full Text Full Text PDF PubMed Scopus (21) Google Scholar opioid harm reduction,10Samuels E.A. Dwyer K. Mello M.J. et al.Emergency department-based opioid harm reduction: moving physicians from willing to doing.Acad Emerg Med. 2016; 23: 455-465Crossref PubMed Scopus (57) Google Scholar and heart failure.11Asthana V. Sundararajan M. Ackah R.L. et al.Heart failure education in the emergency department markedly reduces readmissions in un- and under-insured patients.Am J Emerg Med. 2018; 36: 2166-2171Abstract Full Text Full Text PDF PubMed Scopus (6) Google Scholar Focusing climate change education efforts on providing individualized, evidence-based discharge instructions may be a similarly effective way to provide patients with important resiliency tools based on individual risk factors, such as a patient with diabetes and open wounds who will be traveling to the coast to swim in water with a high prevalence of Vibrio bacteria. In 2019, the American Medical Association passed a resolution supporting teaching on climate change in undergraduate, graduate, and continuing medical education settings.12American Medical AssociationResolution #A19-302: Climate Change Education Across the Medical Education Continuum. Adopted June 2019.https://www.psr.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/ama-climate-change-education-policy-2019.pdfGoogle Scholar Since that time, frameworks that integrate climate change into residency training have been proposed13Philipsborn R.P. Sheffield P. White A. et al.Climate change and the practice of medicine: essentials for resident education.Acad Med. 2021; 96: 355-367Crossref PubMed Scopus (56) Google Scholar and a new generation of physicians trained in climate change and health have emerged as leaders in their communities, utilizing and operationalizing the ever-growing scientific evidence that supports the rapid action for health.14Lemery J. Balbus J. Sorensen C.J. et al.Training clinical and public health leaders in climate and health.Health Aff (Millwood). 2020; 39: 2189-2196Crossref PubMed Scopus (24) Google Scholar Yet, our response to incorporating topics of climate change into the training of emergency physicians at the bedside represents a profound opportunity for growth and improved patient care. Within the Knowledge, Skills and Abilities (KSAs) statements proposed by the American Board of Emergency Medicine, KSAs PE0 (“Prevention and Education”) states that emergency physicians should be able to “lead or participate in programs that educate patients and the community about injury and illness prevention; identify preventive measures to avoid/delay illness or prevent trauma; (and) educate patients regarding preventive measures to improve lifestyle, avoid/delay illness, or prevent trauma, and to optimize patient outcomes.”15American Board of Emergency MedicineKnowledge Skills and Abilities. Approved February 2021.https://www.abem.org/public/resources/emergency-medicine-milestones-ksasGoogle Scholar Incorporating brief climate-focused patient education discussions is a valuable opportunity for supervising faculty to evaluate trainees on their bedside communication and professionalism while weaving threads of climate education into a busy clinical teaching shift. Consider the following cases. Both are clinical presentations that are being amplified by climate change. Both are also scenarios in which taking advantage of a teachable moment may improve patient health resilience and prevent climate-related life-threatening illnesses. Although not comprehensive, our goal is to enhance patient care, particularly for the most vulnerable populations. A 76-year-old woman presented to the ED in July with dizziness. The patient had a history of hypertension and chronic kidney disease. She lived by herself in an apartment with no air conditioning in the suburbs of Chicago. The workup was reassuring and symptoms improved after rehydration and cooling. The patient was discharged home with a diagnosis of heat exhaustion. Heat illness ranges from mild disorders such as heat exhaustion to life-threatening conditions such as heat stroke. Providers and patients should be aware that there is no specific environmental temperature at which heat stroke tends to occur and precautions should be taken even with temperatures as low as 86 °F (30 °C) especially in areas with high relative humidity.16People’s Liberation Army Professional Committee of Critical Care MedicineExpert consensus on standardized diagnosis and treatment for heat stroke.Mil Med Res. 2016; 3: 1PubMed Google Scholar People who are most at risk for heat stroke and who should be considered for patient education include those with chronic diseases, housing insecurity, substance abuse, psychiatric disease, at extremes of ages, and outdoor workers. Medications such as beta blockers, diuretics,17Hausfater P. Megarbane B. Dautheville S. et al.Prognostic factors in non-exertional heatstroke.Intensive Care Med. 2010; 36: 272-280Crossref PubMed Scopus (52) Google Scholar antipsychotics,18Stöllberger C. Lutz W. Finsterer J. Heat-related side-effects of neurological and non-neurological medication may increase heatwave fatalities.Eur J Neurol. 2009; 16: 879-882Crossref PubMed Scopus (51) Google Scholar anticholinergics, and some antidepressants can also predispose to dehydration and increase the risk for heat stroke. Samples of patient education can be found in Appendix E1 (English language) and Appendix E2 (Spanish language) (available at http://www.annemergmed.com). A 14-year-old boy with type I diabetes mellitus presented to the ED with abdominal pain and fatigue. A couple of weeks ago, his home in Virginia lost power after a hurricane made landfall in the United States. The patient was diagnosed with severe hyperglycemia without diabetic ketoacidosis as a result of expired insulin and inability to obtain a new prescription in a timely manner. After receiving intravenous fluids and subcutaneous insulin, he was discharged with a refill of his medications. Morbidity and mortality after extreme weather events amplified by climate change such as hurricanes and floods are complex and oftentimes difficult to quantify. Short-term health effects of extreme weather events include unintentional blunt and thermal injuries, drownings, and exposure to carbon monoxide and accidental chemical releases. These typically account for the majority of deaths reported after weather events. However, this can represent a gross underestimation,19Santos-Lozada A.R. Howard J.T. Use of death counts from vital statistics to calculate excess deaths in Puerto Rico following hurricane Maria.JAMA. 2018; 320: 1491-1493Crossref PubMed Scopus (76) Google Scholar as a substantial portion of morbidity and mortality happens weeks to months after weather events from profound disruptions in environmental and social infrastructures.20Waddell S.L. Jayaweera D.T. Mirsaeidi M. et al.Perspectives on the health effects of hurricanes: a review and challenges.Int J Environ Res Public Health. 2021; 18: 2756Crossref PubMed Scopus (10) Google Scholar During and after storms, certain racial and ethnic groups and low-income communities have higher rates of injury, illness, displacement, and death.21Lane K. Charles-Guzman K. Wheeler K. et al.Health effects of coastal storms and flooding in urban areas: a review and vulnerability assessment.J Environ Public Health. 2013; 2013913064Crossref PubMed Scopus (141) Google Scholar Those with chronic diseases frequently experience a disruption in care, inability to access medications, and higher rates of hospitalization.22Anderson A.H. Cohen A.J. Kutner N.G. et al.Missed dialysis sessions and hospitalization in hemodialysis patients after Hurricane Katrina.Kidney Int. 2009; 75: 1202-1208Abstract Full Text Full Text PDF PubMed Scopus (83) Google Scholar,23Arrieta M.I. Foreman R.D. Crook E.D. et al.Providing continuity of care for chronic diseases in the aftermath of Katrina: from field experience to policy recommendations.Disaster Med Public Health Prep. 2009; 3: 174-182Crossref PubMed Scopus (69) Google Scholar There is also significant increase in ED utilization by older adults predominantly for electrolyte imbalances, dialysis, and medication refill.24Malik S. Lee D.C. Doran K.M. et al.Vulnerability of older adults in disasters: emergency department utilization by geriatric patients after hurricane Sandy.Disaster Med Public Health Prep. 2018; 12: 184-193Crossref PubMed Scopus (56) Google Scholar Samples of patient education can be found in Appendix E3 (English language) and Appendix E4 (Spanish language) (available at http://www.annemergmed.com). Crowding and time constraints of a busy ED often make spending additional time at the patient’s bedside challenging. Additionally, the spectrum of languages and reading comprehension experienced across EDs as well as competing priorities can make it difficult to find a one-size-fits-all patient education model. Better evidence is needed to optimize the organization and delivery of patient education,25Pétré B. Margat A. Servotte J.C. et al.Patient education in the emergency department: take advantage of the teachable moment.Adv Health Sci Educ Theory Pract. 2020; 25: 511-517Crossref PubMed Scopus (12) Google Scholar especially for rapidly evolving public health threats, such as climate change. Yet, there is much we already know that can be better disseminated and acted upon to reduce the demand for care and potentially improve outcomes that matter most to patients. Given the scale in which climate change is already affecting human health and the need for rapid adaptation and improved resilience, considering all manners of patient counseling seems prudent. In addition to provider-patient conversations and traditional written discharge instructions, EDs may consider alternative forms of educating their patients on how climate is affecting their health, such as pictographic illustration26Hill B. Perri-Moore S. Kuang J. et al.Automated pictographic illustration of discharge instructions with glyph: impact on patient recall and satisfaction.J Am Med Inform Assoc. 2016; 23: 1136-1142Crossref PubMed Scopus (27) Google Scholar and short videos. In conclusion, in emergency medicine, we have the unique privilege of interfacing with patients who often have limited means of accessing medical care and face multiple barriers to achieving optimal health. It, therefore, falls under our purview to share the evidence and individualized education to address gaps in awareness and understanding. The potential to reduce adverse clinical outcomes far outweighs our small effort. It is a service to our patients and each other as we attempt to reduce acute care demands and keep our communities healthy. As stakeholders across disciplines and sectors work to limit the adverse effects of global warming, we as clinicians and educators can adapt and promote climate resilient development right in our EDs. Discharge instructions that link climate hazards to health is just one example by which planetary health is integrated with bedside education. Download .docx (.02 MB) Help with docx files Appendix E1 to E4
